{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17509797","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17509797"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:53+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T12:19:53+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11444"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"11444","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/11444"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.17,0.15,0.15,0.04,0.49]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4078"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40568"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"4078","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/4078"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2021-12-16T09:52:03+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-25T09:05:39+10:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-11-25T09:05:39+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-26 19:24:42"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11444"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25345"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"31"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"390"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"4948"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10240"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10340"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25345"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40568","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/40568"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 47-year-old man presents with a two month history of an increasing pain above his right knee. He initially managed this with over-the-counter analgesics, but these do not now give him any relief. His history includes follicular thyroid carcinoma, which was treated with total thyroidectomy and neck dissection two years ago.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination his blood pressure 122/86 mmHg, pulse 80/min, and temperature 37.0\u003Csup\u003Eo\u003C/sup\u003EC. An X-ray is performed (Image). A bone scan shows increased uptake this region, but no other abnormalities. A CT scan confirms this finding and the scans of the abdomen and chest are unremarkable.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate initial plan of management?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Surgery","Chemotherapy","Targeted therapy","Immunotherapy","Radiotherapy"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe patient has presented with an isolated metastatic deposit in the lower end of the right femur. The incidence of osseous recurrence in thyroid cancers is around 4%. \u003Cstrong\u003ERadiotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E is the most appropriate treatment option for this patient with metastatic follicular thyroid carcinoma. Radiotherapy can be administered to the affected bone, and can also be used as an adjunct therapy following surgical resection to decrease the risk of recurrence. It is effective in both reducing the size of the metastatic deposit and preventing further growth. Radiotherapy helps both in pain relief and the destruction of the metastatic deposit. The use of radiotherapy in thyroid carcinoma is well-established, and it is considered a standard of care in the management of advanced thyroid carcinoma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESurgery\u003C/strong\u003E is the primary treatment for thyroid carcinoma and may be indicated for the management of isolated bony metastases in some patients. In the case of isolated metastatic deposits, surgery may be appropriate if the lesion is amenable to complete resection, and if there is no evidence of distant metastases. However, in patients with advanced disease, surgery may not be an appropriate option, as there may be a high risk of morbidity and limited benefit, the incidence of curative osseous metastases is rare.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EChemotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E has limited effectiveness in the treatment of thyroid carcinoma and is not recommended for isolated metastatic deposits. Chemotherapy is generally reserved for cases of advanced thyroid carcinoma with distant metastases, where there are limited treatment options available.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAlthough \u003Cstrong\u003Eimmunotherapy\u003C/strong\u003E has shown promise in the treatment of certain types of cancer, its role in the treatment of thyroid carcinoma is not well-established. The use of immunotherapy is typically limited to patients with advanced thyroid carcinoma who have failed other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ETargeted therapy\u003C/strong\u003E, such as tyrosine kinase inhibitors, has shown efficacy in the treatment of advanced thyroid carcinoma. However, its use is typically reserved for cases with progressive disease or refractory to other treatments. In the case of isolated metastatic deposits, targeted therapy may be appropriate if there is evidence of disease progression or refractory to other treatments.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Radiotherapy is the treatment of choice for an isolated osseous metastatic deposit of thyroid carcinoma."],"references":["I\u00f1iguez-Ariza NM, Bible KC, Clarke BL. Bone metastases in thyroid cancer. J Bone Oncol. 2020 Feb 19;21:100282. doi: 10.1016/j.jbo.2020.100282. PMID: 32154098; PMCID: PMC7058902.","Romesser PB, Sherman EJ, Shaha AR, Lian M, Wong RJ, Sabra M, Rao SS, Fagin JA, Tuttle RM, Lee NY. External beam radiotherapy with or without concurrent chemotherapy in advanced or recurrent non-anaplastic non-medullary thyroid cancer. J Surg Oncol. 2014 Sep;110(4):375-82. doi: 10.1002/jso.23656. Epub 2014 Jun 24. PMID: 24961938."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25345"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"11444"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"20419"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"20419","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/20419"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4RzA6betobR1lEsTon0Eq8mwLWCu2S.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/4RzA6betobR1lEsTon0Eq8mwLWCu2S.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"25345","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/25345"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2023-11-25T09:03:48+10:30","updatedAt":"2023-11-25T09:03:48+10:30","number":7,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":null,"plagiarismScore":null,"plagiarismReportUrl":null},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"4078"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"40568"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"9"}},"generation":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"31","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/31"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83c\udf97","name":"Oncology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:45+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"66","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/66"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Management","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}